## RESEARCH SUMMARY

### Area 1: `__del__` Objects in `gc.garbage`

**Primary source**: `Python/gc.c` (NOT `Modules/gcmodule.c` — that is just the Python interface)

**Key distinction: `tp_del` vs `tp_finalize`**

- `tp_del` = the **legacy** (pre-PEP 442) slot. Set when a Python class defines `__del__` the old way. `has_legacy_finalizer()` at gc.c:678–682 checks `Py_TYPE(op)->tp_del != NULL`.
- `tp_finalize` = the **PEP 442** (Python 3.4+) slot. Modern `__del__` populates this slot instead. Called by `finalize_garbage()` at gc.c:1046–1076, which checks `!_PyGC_FINALIZED(op) && tp_finalize != NULL`. Objects using `tp_finalize` CAN be collected normally — they do NOT land in `gc.garbage`.

**Collection cycle sequence** (gc.c:1531–1606):
1. `move_legacy_finalizers(&unreachable, &finalizers)` — gc.c:1537: scans `unreachable`, moves every object where `tp_del != NULL` into `finalizers` list. Also clears `NEXT_MASK_UNREACHABLE` flag.
2. `move_legacy_finalizer_reachable(&finalizers)` — gc.c:1542: pulls objects reachable from those finalizers out of `unreachable` too.
3. `handle_weakref_callbacks()` — gc.c:1555.
4. `finalize_garbage(tstate, &unreachable)` — gc.c:1560: calls `tp_finalize` on remaining unreachable objects (the PEP 442 path).
5. `handle_resurrected_objects()` — gc.c:1566: reachable survivors go back to old generation.
6. `delete_garbage()` — gc.c:1581: clears cycles via `tp_clear`. At gc.c:1095–1098, `DEBUG_SAVEALL` adds all objects to `gcstate->garbage`.
7. **`handle_legacy_finalizers(tstate, gcstate, &finalizers, old)`** — gc.c:1605: this is where `gc.garbage` gets populated.

**Exact condition causing append to `gc.garbage`** — gc.c:1030:
```c
if ((gcstate->debug & _PyGC_DEBUG_SAVEALL) || has_legacy_finalizer(op)) {
    if (PyList_Append(gcstate->garbage, op) < 0) { ... }
}
```
Translation: an object lands in `gc.garbage` iff `DEBUG_SAVEALL` is set **OR** it has `tp_del` (the old-style `__del__`). Objects using only `tp_finalize` (modern `__del__`) are NOT added.

**`gc_list_merge()` — gc.c:276–293**: appends list `from` onto `to` by relinking `to`'s tail to `from`'s head, then reinitializes `from` as empty. Used at end of `handle_legacy_finalizers()` (gc.c:1038) to merge `finalizers` into the old generation (`old`), making those objects live again (permanent survivors of collection).

**PEP 442 behavior change**: Before Python 3.4, ALL objects with `__del__` used `tp_del`, so all cyclic-garbage objects with `__del__` ended in `gc.garbage`. Since 3.4, CPython populates `tp_finalize` for new-style `__del__`, so those objects can be collected normally — they only end up in `gc.garbage` if part of an unreachable cycle and they have `tp_del` (only old extension types / C-level overrides).

