### Area 6: `list.rotate(n)` Stub

**`PyListObject` struct** (listobject.c: inferred from usage):
- `self->ob_item`: `PyObject **` — pointer to backing array of object pointers
- `Py_SIZE(self)`: `Py_ssize_t` — current number of elements (via `ob_base.ob_size`)
- `self->allocated`: `Py_ssize_t` — allocated capacity

**`reverse_slice()`** — listobject.c:1619–1633:
```c
static void
reverse_slice(PyObject **lo, PyObject **hi)
{
    assert(lo && hi);
    --hi;
    while (lo < hi) {
        PyObject *t = *lo;
        FT_ATOMIC_STORE_PTR_RELEASE(*lo, *hi);
        FT_ATOMIC_STORE_PTR_RELEASE(*hi, t);
        ++lo;
        --hi;
    }
}
```
Note: uses `FT_ATOMIC_STORE_PTR_RELEASE` for thread safety in free-threaded builds.

**`list_reverse_impl()`** — listobject.c:3234–3239:
```c
static PyObject *
list_reverse_impl(PyListObject *self)
{
    if (Py_SIZE(self) > 1)
        reverse_slice(self->ob_item, self->ob_item + Py_SIZE(self));
    Py_RETURN_NONE;
}
```
No concurrent-modification guard inside `list_reverse_impl` itself. The `@critical_section` in the clinic block (line 3227) holds the lock for the entire operation — that IS the concurrency guard.

**Argument Clinic block for `list.insert`** (template for `list.rotate`) — listobject.c:1171–1184:
```c
/*[clinic input]
@critical_section
list.insert

    index: Py_ssize_t
    object: object
    /

Insert object before index.
[clinic start generated code]*/
```

**`list_methods[]`** — listobject.c:3597–3615:
- Last real entry before sentinel: `LIST_SORT_METHODDEF` at line 3612 (then `{"__class_getitem__", ...}` at 3613)
- Sentinel `{NULL, NULL}` at line 3614
- Insert `LIST_ROTATE_METHODDEF` at line 3612 (before `LIST_SORT_METHODDEF`) or after it

**Concurrent modification guard pattern**: The `@critical_section` in the clinic block handles it. `list_reverse_impl` itself does NOT recheck size; `rotate` should follow the same pattern (no manual version check needed).

**Complete two-piece stub**:

```c
/* Helper: reverse arr[lo..hi) in-place */
static void
_list_reverse_slice(PyObject **arr, Py_ssize_t lo, Py_ssize_t hi)
{
    PyObject **p = arr + lo;
    PyObject **q = arr + hi - 1;
    while (p < q) {
        PyObject *t = *p;
        FT_ATOMIC_STORE_PTR_RELEASE(*p, *q);
        FT_ATOMIC_STORE_PTR_RELEASE(*q, t);
        ++p;
        --q;
    }
}

/*[clinic input]
@critical_section
list.rotate
    n: Py_ssize_t
    /

Rotate the list in-place by n steps (positive = left/shift-toward-front, negative = right).
[clinic start generated code]*/

static PyObject *
list_rotate_impl(PyListObject *self, Py_ssize_t n)
/*[clinic end generated code: ...]*/
{
    Py_ssize_t len = Py_SIZE(self);
    if (len <= 1)
        Py_RETURN_NONE;

    n %= len;
    if (n < 0)
        n += len;
    if (n == 0)
        Py_RETURN_NONE;

    /* Left-rotate by n: equivalent to three reverses.
       Original: [0..n) [n..len)
       After:    [n..len) [0..n)
    */
    PyObject **arr = self->ob_item;
    _list_reverse_slice(arr, 0, n);        /* reverse prefix   */
    _list_reverse_slice(arr, n, len);      /* reverse suffix   */
    _list_reverse_slice(arr, 0, len);      /* reverse all      */

    Py_RETURN_NONE;
}
```

**Key gotcha**: CPython's `list.rotate` should match `collections.deque.rotate` semantics where **positive n = right rotation** (last element moves to front). Verify the deque convention before committing to the lo/hi expressions above (the stub above uses positive = left; swap if needed).

