### Collection cycle order (gc.c ~lines 1532–1605)
1. `move_legacy_finalizers(&unreachable, &finalizers)` — separate tp_del objects
2. `move_legacy_finalizer_reachable(&finalizers)` — add reachable-from-finalizers objects
3. `handle_weakref_callbacks(&unreachable, old)` — clear/invoke weakrefs
4. **`finalize_garbage(tstate, &unreachable)`** — call tp_finalize (PEP 442 new path)
5. `handle_resurrected_objects(...)` — resurrection handling
6. `clear_weakrefs(&final_unreachable)`
7. **`delete_garbage(tstate, gcstate, &final_unreachable, old)`** — call tp_clear, free objects
8. **`handle_legacy_finalizers(tstate, gcstate, &finalizers, old)`** — append to gc.garbage

### tp_del vs tp_finalize
- **`tp_del`** (`Include/cpython/object.h:223`): pre-PEP 442 legacy finalizer (`destructor tp_del`).  Objects with tp_del are separated EARLY; they are NEVER freed by the collector — they always end up in `gc.garbage` (unless debug flags prevent it).
- **`tp_finalize`** (`Include/cpython/object.h:230`): PEP 442 (Python 3.4+) finalizer.  Objects can be collected after finalization.  Resurrection is detected and handled by `handle_resurrected_objects`.
- `_PyGC_FINALIZED(op)` reads bit 0 of `gc->_gc_prev` (`_PyGC_PREV_MASK_FINALIZED = 1`, line 117 of `Include/internal/pycore_gc.h`).

### PEP 442 vs pre-3.4
Comment at line 678: "Return true if object has a pre-PEP 442 finalization method."
Before Python 3.4: ALL objects with `__del__` in a reference cycle went to gc.garbage.
Python 3.4+ (PEP 442): `tp_finalize` allows finalization + potential collection; only tp_del objects still go to gc.garbage.

Python-level `__del__` maps to `tp_finalize` (via `slot_tp_finalize` in typeobject.c) — so pure-Python `__del__` classes use PEP 442 path and do NOT automatically go to gc.garbage in cycles.

