### Loop pattern for find_all (non-overlapping)

Key insight: `stringlib_find_slice(str, len, sub, sub_len, pos, end)` returns absolute index or -1.
After each match at index `found`, advance `pos = found + sub_len` (non-overlapping).
Special case: if `sub_len == 0`, advance by 1 to avoid infinite loop.

```c
Py_buffer subbuf;
if (PyObject_GetBuffer(sub, &subbuf, PyBUF_SIMPLE) < 0)
    return NULL;
const char *sub_str = subbuf.buf;
Py_ssize_t sub_len = subbuf.len;

PyObject *list = PyList_New(0);
if (list == NULL) { PyBuffer_Release(&subbuf); return NULL; }

Py_ssize_t pos = start;
Py_ssize_t step = (sub_len == 0) ? 1 : sub_len;
while (pos <= end - sub_len) {
    Py_ssize_t found = stringlib_find_slice(str, len, sub_str, sub_len, pos, end);
    if (found < 0) break;
    PyObject *item = PyLong_FromSsize_t(found);
    if (item == NULL || PyList_Append(list, item) < 0) {
        Py_XDECREF(item); Py_DECREF(list); PyBuffer_Release(&subbuf); return NULL;
    }
    Py_DECREF(item);
    pos = found + step;
}
PyBuffer_Release(&subbuf);
return list;
```

NOTE: `stringlib_find_slice` is a macro-generated name. In bytes_methods.c it's available as `stringlib_find_slice` because bytes_methods.c includes `stringlib/find.h` after setting `STRINGLIB_CHAR = char`.

